text:
*Random Helpful Tip (that I often give directly to people, but figured I'd include it here):* If you have a website, you can eliminate the need for a secondary "Links" site (such as Linktree) by simply creating your own on your website. You can even hide it from the normal navigation bar, so you only access it from where you've intentionally linked it (such as your IG). Also, if you have a newsletter, you can include a signup below the links! Makes signing up easier for anyone wanting to. This also doubles as directing traffic to your website, which makes search engines (such as Google) recognize it as more popular and it is then likely to be shown higher in search results.

*Important Note:* Part of why this is so helpful is that most social media platforms notoriously suppress any use of the word "link" - including in "linktree". So, posts that include mention of linktree or statements like "link in BIO" are usually suppressed in the algorithms. (That's why people often use a chainlink emote instead of the word!) This is because the companies that own them (such as Meta) don't WANT you to direct people to other websites - they want users to stay on THEIR website. This has been shown through a lot of users doing A / B testing over the years; results typically showed that posts that included words like "link" would get almost no traction (if any at all) and the exact same posts without the word "link" would reach users/followers perfectly fine.

Included images to show my link of my IG and my link page on my website. ALSO, note, I should probably change the URL to NOT include the word "links" in it. I just haven't got around to it, yet. ^_^;;

